com.ibm.team.scm.common.dto

Interface IChangeHistorySyncReport


  • public interface IChangeHistorySyncReport
    Represents the relative synchronization of a pair of change histories, termed the local and the remote, and provides the information needed to transfer changes sets between them.

    The terms "local" and "remote" are only relative to the context in which this report was generated - there is no implication as to where in the network these change histories or components originated. As used here, "local" means the change history or workspace that initiated the compare (the "lhs") and "remote" refers to the argument of that compare (the "rhs").

    TODO Issue: The sync report should include more information about the change sets, such as: an indication of which change sets are active: dependencies among the incoming (outgoing) change sets; overlaps between incoming and outgoing change sets.

    Since:
    0.5

    • Method Detail

      • localComponents

        java.util.List localComponents()
        Returns the components known to the local workspace or change history.

        If this report was generated in a workspace context, then the components returned represent those known to the workspace that initiated the report, omitting any components were explicitly excluded. If the report was generated in a change history context, then there will be a single component returned, that referenced by the change history that initiated the report. Note that in the change history context, the single component returned by this method and remoteComponents() will be the same.

        If you need to know what components were added/removed from the local and remote workspaces, you will need to compare the value of this method with that of remoteComponents().

        Returns:
        the possibly empty list of components (element type: IComponentHandle) known to the local workspace or change history; unmodifiable list; never null

      • remoteComponents

        java.util.List remoteComponents()
        Returns the components known to the remote workspace or change history.

        If this report was generated in a workspace context, then the components returned represent those known to the workspace that was the target of this report, omitting any components were explicitly excluded. If the report was generated in a change history context, then there will be a single component returned, that referenced by the change history that is the target of this report. Note that in the change history context, the single component returned by this method and localComponents() will be the same.

        If you need to know what components were added/removed from the local and remote workspaces, you will need to compare the value of this method with that of localComponents().

        Returns:
        the possibly empty list of components (element type: IComponentHandle) known to the remote workspace or change history; unmodifiable list; never null

      • incomingChangeSets

        java.util.List incomingChangeSets(IComponentHandle component)
        Returns the list of change sets already incorporated into the remote change history that are not present in the local change history for the given component. Returns the empty list if the component is not present in the local change history.

        The order of the change sets in the result reflects their relative order in the remote history for that component.

        Note that the result may include active change sets, which the client would usually not consider as "incoming".

        Parameters:
        component - the component; must not be null
        Returns:
        the possibly empty list of incoming change sets for the given component (element type: IChangeSetHandle); unmodifiable list; never null

      • localBases

        java.util.Map localBases()
        Returns the bases known to the local workspace or change history.

        If this report was generated in a workspace context, then the components returned represent those known to the workspace that initiated the report, omitting any components were explicitly excluded. If the report was generated in any other context, this routine shall return an empty list.

        Returns:
        a map (key type: IComponentHandle value type: IBaselineHandle) which map components to their basis baseline handle in this workspace. If a component does not have a basis in this workspace, then there is no element value in the map for it. Never null.

      • remoteBases

        java.util.Map remoteBases()
        Returns the bases known to the remote workspace or change history.

        If this report was generated in a workspace context, then the components returned represent those known to the workspace targeted by the operation the report, omitting any components were explicitly excluded. If the report was generated in any other context, this routine shall return an empty list.

        Returns:
        a map (key type: IComponentHandle value type: IBaselineHandle) which map components to their basis baseline handle in this workspace. If a component does not have a basis in this workspace, then there is no element value in the map for it. Never null.

      • incomingBaselines

        java.util.List incomingBaselines(IComponentHandle component)
        Returns the list of baselines that were bases of the remote change history for the given component, and that were not bases of the local change history after the local change history's basis for the component.

        Returns the empty list if the component is not present in the local change history.

        The order of the baselines in the result reflects the order in which they were bases in the remote history, in reverse chronological order.

        Note that this list is not populated unless the report was generated from a service API that explicitly asked to includes the extended information.

        Parameters:
        component - the component; must not be null
        Returns:
        the possibly empty list of incoming baselines for the given component (element type: IBaselineHandle); ordered in reverse chronological order according to when they appeared in the remote change history; unmodifiable list; never null

      • incomingBaselines

        java.util.List incomingBaselines()
        Returns the list of baselines (in all component silos) that were bases of the remote change history that were not bases of the local change history after the local change history's bases.

        The order of the baselines in the result reflects the order in which they were bases in the remote history, in reverse chronological order for each component.

        Note that this list is not populated unless the report was generated from a service API that explicitly asked to includes the extended information.

        Returns:
        the possibly empty list of incoming baselines (element type: IBaselineHandle); ordered in reverse chronological order according to when they appeared in the remote change history; unmodifiable list; never null

      • getIncomingChangeSetCopies

        java.util.List<IChangeSetHandle> getIncomingChangeSetCopies()
        All the incoming change sets which ones have the same port id as a change set already in the local change history, This will identify the incoming change sets while not physically in the change history, they are logically already in the change history.

        Do not make assumptions of the port derivation relationship between the 2 change sets (one in local change history and one in remote change history). One could be the direct port of the other or they can be indirectly ports of one another or simply ports (possibly indirect) of a common change set.

        Returns:
        the possibly empty list of incoming change sets where an equivalent (port) change set exists within the local change history; unmodifiable list; never null

      • getIncomingChangeSetCopies

        java.util.List<IChangeSetHandle> getIncomingChangeSetCopies(IComponentHandle component)
        All the incoming change sets which ones have the same port id as a change set already in the local change history of a particular component, This will identify the incoming change sets while not physically in the change history, they are logically already in the change history.

        Do not make assumptions of the port derivation relationship between the 2 change sets (one in local change history and one in remote change history). One could be the direct port of the other or they can be indirectly ports of one another or simply ports (possibly indirect) of a common change set.

        Returns the empty list if the component is not present in the local change history.

        Parameters:
        component - the component; must not be null
        Returns:
        the possibly empty list of incoming change sets where an equivalent (port) change set exists within the local component's change history; unmodifiable list; never null
